Got it. I was trying to write a tiny TCP server with Node.js just to test this. Here’s what I have:

```javascript
const net = require('net');

const server = new net.Server();
server.listen(0, () => console.log('Listening on port', server.address().port));
server.on('connection', (socket) => {
  socket.write('Hello from TCP!\n');
});
```
It works locally but fails in CI.

You don’t have to do raw sockets at all—just use a non‑blocking event loop and let Node handle TLS asynchronously. Here’s an example:

```javascript
const { Server } = require('http');
const server = new Server((req, res) => {
  const data = Buffer.concat(['Hello from TLS!', '\n']);
  res.end(data);
});

server.listen(3001, () => console.log('TLS‑enabled HTTP on 3001'));
```
Node will perform the handshake in a background thread and return quickly. Your CI can stay within the timeout.
